properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: ROAD DUST ADVISORY IN EFFECT FOR VERNON (February 10, 2021 - Vernon) The Ministry of Environment and Climate Change Strategy in collaboration with Interior Health has continued a Road Dust Advisory issued on February 9, 2021 for Vernon due to high concentrations of coarse particulate matter that are expected to persist until there is precipitation, dust suppression or a change in traffic patterns. Levels tend to be highest around busy roads and industrial operations. This advisory is in effect until further notice. Exposure is particularly a concern for pregnant women, infants, and older adults, as well as, individuals with conditions such as asthma, COPD, heart disease, diabetes or respiratory infections such as COVID-19. Persons with chronic underlying medical conditions or acute infections should postpone or reduce strenuous exercise until the advisory is lifted. Where appropriate, maintain physical distancing. Anyone experiencing symptoms such as continuing eye or throat irritation, chest discomfort, shortness of breath, cough or wheezing, should follow the advice of their health care provider. Real-time air quality observations and information regarding the health effects of air pollution can be found at: https://www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/environment/air-land-water/air ### For more information on current air quality, visit www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/environment/air-land-water/air. Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of severely cold wind chills continues. Extreme cold will persist for a few more days. An Arctic ridge of high pressure has allowed for a very cold air mass to settle over southern Saskatchewan and southern Manitoba. Along with winds of 10 to 20 km/h, extreme wind chill values between -40 and -50 are occurring over most of southern Manitoba and Saskatchewan again tonight. The bitterly cold air will remain over the Prairies for the next few days. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. For more information on cold and your health, visit Manitoba Health at https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/environmentalhealth/cold.html or call Health Links - Info Santé at 204-788-8200 or toll-free at 1-888-315-9257. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Arctic Outflow Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong outflow winds and cold wind chill values are expected or occurring. Arctic air combined with strong outflow winds will continue to generate wind chill values of minus 20 across the coastal and inland sections of the north and central coasts. Wind chill values will moderate through the weekend as the arctic air retreats away from the coast. ### Frostbite and hypothermia can occur within minutes if adequate precautions are not taken when outdoors. Arctic outflow warnings are issued when bitterly cold air flows from the interior to coastal communities and the outflow winds create wind chill values of -20 or less for 6 hours or more. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy snowfall with blowing snow is expected. Additional snowfall: 10 cm except locally 20 cm in areas of heaviest snow. Maximum wind gusts: westerly 80 km/h. Locations: St. John's and vicinity and the Avalon Peninsula North. Time span: tonight into Friday morning. Remarks: Some persistent heavier bands of snow are making for more rapid snowfall accumulation in some areas. The snow, combined with the strong westerly winds, are causing widespread blowing snow with occasional near zero visibilities. Additionally, high drifts are forming in some areas which could be hazardous if met unexpectedly while driving. Conditions will improve Friday morning as the winds and snow ease somewhat and temperatures rise, however periods of snow are likely to continue throughout the day. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills continues. Arctic air over the region is giving extreme cold wind chill values of near minus 40 to minus 45. In northern BC, temperatures remain cold and wind chill values reaching minus 45 are still expected tonight. In the central BC interior wind chill values near minus 40 are forecast to redevelop tonight. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Arctic Outflow Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Wind chill values will range from minus 10 to minus 20. Rising surface pressures over the BC interior will continue to drive arctic air through mainland valleys and inlets. Frigid temperatures and strong outflow winds are expected. Temperatures will begin to rebound over the weekend. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of severely cold wind chills continues. Extreme cold will persist for a few more days. An Arctic ridge of high pressure has allowed for a very cold air mass to settle over southern Saskatchewan and southern Manitoba. Along with winds of 10 to 20 km/h, extreme wind chill values between -40 and -50 are occurring over most of southern Manitoba and Saskatchewan again tonight. The bitterly cold air will remain over the Prairies for the next few days. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Large waves and pounding surf is expected Friday. Locations: from Notre Dame Bay to Cape Race. Remarks: A combination of wind driven waves and large northeasterly swell will cause higher than normal water levels along the entire northeast coast on Friday. The combination of large waves and tides may lead to a risk of minor coastal flooding and infrastructure damage. The greatest risk will occur during high tides on Friday morning and Friday evening. By Saturday, the risk is expected to drop due to subsiding wave heights. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Potential for significant snowfall expected late Friday night and Saturday. Pacific moisture will begin to collide with the arctic front along Vancouver Island Friday night. Snow that is forecast to start near midnight on Friday will persist through Saturday morning. It's uncertain at this time how much snow will fall, but computer models are beginning to agree on amounts ranging between 5 to 15 cm depending on location and elevation. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
